# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: basil
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Cloez identified and ascribed the name "eucalyptol" to the dominant portion of *Eucalyptus globulus* oil.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Because of its pleasant, spicy aroma and taste, eucalyptol is used in flavorings, fragrances, and cosmetics.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Cineole-based eucalyptus oil is used as a flavoring at low levels (0.002%) in various products, including baked goods, confectionery, meat products, and beverages.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] In a 1994 report released by five top cigarette companies, eucalyptol was listed as one of the 599 additives to cigarettes.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] It is claimed to be added to improve the flavor.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Eucalyptol is an ingredient in commercial mouthwashes and cough suppressants.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Eucalyptol exhibits insecticidal and insect repellent properties.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] In contrast, eucalyptol is one of many compounds that are attractive to males of various species of orchid bees, which gather the chemical to synthesize pheromones; it is commonly used as bait to attract and collect these bees for study.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] One such study with *Euglossa imperialis*, a nonsocial orchid bee species, has shown that the presence of cineole (also eucalyptol) elevates territorial behavior and specifically attracts the male bees.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] It was even observed that these males would periodically leave their territories to forage for chemicals such as cineole, thought to be important for attracting and mating with females, to synthesize pheromones.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Eucalyptol has a toxicity (LD50) of 2.48 grams per kg (rat).
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Ingestion in significant quantities is likely to cause headache and gastric distress, such as nausea and vomiting.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Because of its low viscosity, it may directly enter the lungs if swallowed, or if subsequently vomited.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Once in the lungs, it is difficult to remove and can cause delirium, convulsions, severe injury or death.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Consequently, eucalyptol should never be ingested unless in highly diluted formulations.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Toxicity is significantly reduced when administered topically.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] However it should not be used topically during pregnancy, breastfeeding, or on children under two.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Eucalyptol is generated from geranyl pyrophosphate (GPP) which isomerizes to (*S*)-linalyl diphosphate (LPP).
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] Ionization of the pyrophosphate, catalyzed by cineole synthase, produces eucalyptol.
[src:basil/1-8-cineole] The process involves the intermediacy of alpha-terpinyl cation.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In humans, arachidonate 12-lipoxygenase (12-LO, 12-LOX, ALO12, or platelet type 12-lipoxygenase) is encoded by the ALOX12 gene and expressed primarily in platelets and skin.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Arachidonate 12-lipoxygenase, 12R type, also termed 12RLOX and encoded by the ALOX12B gene, is expressed primarily in skin and cornea; it metabolizes arachidonic acid to 12(*R*)-HpETE.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Cytochrome P450 enzymes convert arachidonic acid to a variety of hydroperoxy, epoxy, and dihydroxy derivatives including racemic mixtures of 12(*S*)-HpETE and 12(*R*)-HpETE or 12(*S*)-HETE and 12(*R*)-HETE; the *R* stereoisomer predominates in these mixtures.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Mice also express an epidermal type 15-lipoxygenase (e-12LO) which has 50.8% amino acid sequence identity to human 15-LOX-2 and 49.3% sequence identity to mouse arachidonate 8-lipoxygenase.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Mouse e-12LO metabolizes arachidonic acid predominantly to 12(*S*)-HETE and to a lesser extent 15(*S*)-HETE.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Sub-human primates, although not extensively examined, appear to have 12-lipoxygenase expression patterns that resemble those of sub-primate mammals or humans depending on the closeness of there genetic relatedness to these species.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In human (and mouse) skin epidermis, 12(*R*)-HpETE is metabolized by Epidermis-type lipoxygenase, i.e. eLOX3 (encoded by the ALOXE3 gene), to two products: a) a specific hepoxilin, 8*R*-hydroxy-11*R*,12*R*-epoxy-5*Z*,9*E*,14*Z*-eicosatetraenoic acid (i.e.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These decompositions may occur during tissue isolation procedures.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In other tissues and animal species, numerous hepoxilins form but the hepoxilin synthase activity responsible for their formation is variable.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Thus, the production of hepoxilins from 12(S)-HpETE may result from the intrinsic activity of platelet or leukocyte type 12-LOX's, require eLOX3, or even result from 12(*S*)-HpETE spontaneous (and perhaps artefactual) decomposition during isolation.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The majority of reports on hepoxilin formation have not defined the pathways evolved.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Human and other mammalian cytochrome P450 enzymes convert 12(*S*)-HpETE to 12-oxo-ETE.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12-HETE (stereoisomer not determined), 12(*S*)-HETE, 12-oxo-ETE, hepoxilin B3, and trioxilin B3 are found in the *sn*-2 position of phospholipids isolated from normal human epidermis and human psoriatic scales.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] This indicates that the metabolites are acylated into the *sn*-2 position after being formed and/or directly produced by the metabolism of the arachidonic acid at the *sn*-2 position of these phospholipids.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These acylation reactions may sequester and thereby inactivate or store the metabolites for release during cell stimulation.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The G protein-coupled receptor, GPR31, cloned from PC3 human prostate cancer cell line is a high affinity (Kd=4.8 nM) receptor for 12(*S*)-HETE; GPR31 does not bind 12(*R*)-HETE and has relatively little affinity for 5(*S*)-HETE or 15(*S*)-HETE.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In PC-3 prostate cancer cells, GPR31 receptor mediates the action of 12(*S*)-HETE in activating the mitogen-activated protein kinase kinase/extracellular signal-regulated kinases-1/2 pathway and NFκB pathway that lead to cell growth and other functions.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Studies have not yet determined the role, if any, in GPR31 receptor in the action of 12(*S*)-HETE in other cell types.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A G protein-coupled receptor for the 5(*S*),12(*R*)-dihydroxy metabolite of arachidonic acid, leukotriene B4, vis., leukotriene B4 receptor 2 (BLT2), but not its leukotriene B4 receptor 1, mediates responses to 12(*S*)-HETE, 12(*R*)-HETE, and 12-oxo-ETE in many cell types.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The BLT2 receptor, in contrast to the GPR31 receptor, appears to be expressed at a high level in a wide range of tissues including neutrophils, eosinophils, monocytes, spleen, liver, and ovary.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] However, 12-hydroxyheptadecatrienoic acid (i.e.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12-(*S*)-hydroxy-5*Z*,8*E*,10*E*-heptadecatrienoic acid or 12-HHT), a product made when prostaglandin H2 is metabolized to thromboxane A2 by thromboxane synthase or spontaneously rearranges non-enzymatically is the most potent BLT2 receptor agonist detected to date.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Ultimately, both receptors and all three ligands may prove to be responsible for some tissue responses in vivo.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12(*S*)-HETE and 12(*R*)-HETE bind to and act as competitive antagonists of the thromboxane receptor which mediates the actions of thromboxane A2 and prostaglandin H2.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] This antagonistic activity was responsible for the ability of 12(*S*)-HETE and 12(*R*)-HETE to relax mouse mesenteric arteries pre-constricted with a thromboxane A2 mimetic, U46619.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12(*S*)-HETE binds with high affinity to a 50 kilodalton (kDa) subunit of a 650 kDa cytosolic and nuclear protein complex.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Since it mediates 12(*S*)-HETE-induced itching in the mouse model, BLT2 rather than GPR31 may mediate human itch in these reactions.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12-HETE (stereoisomer not defined) is the dominant arachidonic acid metabolite in cultured PC3 human prostate cancer cells and its levels in human prostate cancer tissue exceed by >9-fold its levels in normal human prostate tissue.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These results suggest that the 12(*S*)-HETE made by prostate cancer tissues serves to promote the growth and spread of this cancer.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Since it mediates the action of 12(*S*)-HETE in stimulating cultured PC3 cells to activate the mitogen-activated protein kinase kinase/extracellular signal-regulated kinases-1/2 pathway and NFκB pathways, the GPR31 receptor may contribute to the pro-malignant activity of 12(*S*)-HETE.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Thus, the role of 12(*S*)-HETE in human prostate cancer, if any, may involve its activation of one or both of the GPR31 and BLT2 receptors.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These studies implicate the interaction of 12-HETE with BLT2 receptors in intestinal epithelium cancer cells, and BLT2 receptors in breast, ovary, pancreas, and bladder cancer cells.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] While the studies on these tissues have not been as frequent or diverse as those on prostate cancer cell lines, they are suggested to indicate that 12-HETE contributes to the growth or spread of the corresponding cancer in humans.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12(S)-HETE, 12(*S*)-HpETE, and with far less potency 12(*R*)-HETE reduced insulin secretion and caused apoptosis in cultured human pancreatic insulin-secreting beta cell lines and prepared pancreatic islets.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12-lipoxygenase-knockout mice (i.e., mice genetically manipulated to remove the Alox12, i.e.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12-lipoxygenase gene, see Lipoxygenase § Mouse lipoxygenases) are resistant to **a)** streptozotocin-induced, **b)** high fat diet-induced, and **c)** autoimmune-induced diabetes.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Further studies in animal models suggest that the 12*S*-HETE made by pancreatic beta cells (or possibly alpha cells or other cell types indigenous to or invading the pancreatic islands) orchestrate a local immune response that results in the injury and, when extreme, death of beta cells.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These results suggest that the 12-lipoxygenase-12S-HETE pathway is one factor contributing to immunity-based type I diabetes as well as low insulin output type II diabetes.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The vasodilating effect on mouse mesenteric arteries appears due to 12*S*-HETE's ability to act as a thromboxane receptor antagonist and thereby block the vasoconstricting actions of thromboxane A2.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These results indicate that the cited metabolites have dilating or constricting effects that depend on the arterial vascular site and or species of animal examined; their role in human blood pressure regulation is unclear.
[src:basil/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Excessive 12-HETE production is implicated in psoriasis.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Some recent studies measuring HODE levels in tissue have lumped the four 9-HODEs with the four 13-HODEs to report only on total HODEs (tHODEs). tHODEs have been proposed to be markers for certain human diseases.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The enzyme acts in a highly stereospecific manner, forming 13(*S*)-hydroperoxy-9*Z*,11*E*-octadecadienoic acid (13(*S*)-HpODE) but comparatively little or no 13(*R*)-hydroperoxy-9*Z*,11*E*-octadecadienoic acid (13(*R*)-HpODE) -.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In cells, 13(*S*)-HpODE is rapidly reduced by peroxidases to 13(*S*)-HODE.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] ALOX15 is fully capable of metabolizing the linoleic acid that is bound to phospholipid or cholesterol to form 13(S)-HpODE-bound phospholipids and cholesterol that are rapidly converted to their corresponding 13(S)-HODE-bound products.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Concurrently with their production of 13(*S*)-HODE, these enzymes also produce smaller amounts of 9(*R*)-HODE.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Cytochrome P450 microsomal enzymes metabolize linoleic acid to a mixture of 13-HODEs and 9-HODEs; these reactions produce racemic mixtures in which the *R* stereoisomer predominates, for instance by a *R*/*S* ratio of 80%/20% for both 13-HODE and 9-HODE in human liver microsomes.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 4-hydroxy-2*E*-nonenal or HNE) is also a peroxidation product of 13-HpODE.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Since oxidative stress commonly produces both free radicals and singlet oxygen, most or all of these products may form together in tissues undergoing oxidative stress.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Free radical and singlet oxygen oxidations of linoleic acid produce a similar set of 13-HODE metabolites (see 9-Hydroxyoctadecadienoic acid).
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Studies attribute these oxidations to be major contributors to 13-HODE production in tissues undergoing oxidative stress including in humans sites of inflammation, steatohepatitis, cardiovascular disease-related atheroma plaques, neurodegenerative disease, etc.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13(*S*)-HODE is also metabolized by peroxisome-dependent β-oxidations to chain-shortened 16-carbon, 14-carbon, and 12-carbon products which are released from the cell; this chain-shortening pathway may serve to inactive and dispose of 13(*S*)-HODE.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13(*S*)-HODE is oxidized to 13-oxo-9*Z*,11*E*-octadecadienoic acid (13-oxo-HODE or 13-oxoODE) by a NAD+-dependent 13-HODE dehydrogenase, the protein for which has been partially purified from rat colon.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Colonic mucosal explants from Sprague-Dawley rats and human colon cancer HT29 cells add glutathione to 13-oxo-ODE in a Michael reaction to form 13-oxo-9-glutatione-11(*E*)-octadecenoic acid; this conjugation reaction appears to be enzymatic and mediated by a glutathione transferase.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Since this conjugate may be rapidly exported from the cell and has not yet been characterized for biological activity, it is not clear if this transferase reaction serves any function beyond removing 13-oxo-ODE from the cell to limit its activity.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13-HODE, 13-oxoODE, and 13-EE-HODE (along with their 9-HODE counterparts) directly activate peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPARγ).
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] This activation appears responsible for the ability of 13-HODE (and 9-HODE) to induce the transcription of PPARγ-inducible genes in human monocytes as well as to stimulate the maturation of these cells to macrophages.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13(*S*)-HODE, 13(*R*)-HODE and 13-oxoODE, along with their 9-HODE counterparts, also act on cells through TRPV1.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] TRPV1 is the transient receptor potential cation channel subfamily V member 1 receptor (also termed capsaicin receptor or vanilloid receptor 1).
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The OXLAM-TRPV1 interaction is credited with mediating pain sensation in rodents (see below).
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13(*S*)-HpODE, and 13(*S*)-HODE directly activate human (but not mouse) GPR132 (G protein coupled receptor 132, also termed G2A) in Chinese hamster ovary cells made to express these receptors; they are, however, far weaker GPR132 activators than 9(*S*)-HpODE or 9(*S*)-HODE.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] GPR132 was initially described as a pH sensing receptor; the role(s) of 13(*S*)-HpODE and 13(*S*)-HODE as well as 9(*S*)-HpODE, 9(*S*)HODE, and a series or GPR132-activating arachidonic acid hydroxy metabolites (i.e.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] HETEs) in activating G2A under the physiological and pathological conditions in which G2A is implicated (see GPR132 for a lists of these conditions) have not yet been determined.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] This determination, as it might apply to humans, is made difficult by the inability of these HODEs to activate rodent GPR132 and therefore to be analyzed in rodent models.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] It is suggested that the accumulation of phospholipid-bound 13(*S*)-HpODE and/or 13(*S*)-HODE is a critical step in rendering mitochondria more permeable thereby triggering their degradation and thence maturation to erythrocytes.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] However, functional inactivation of the phospholipid-attacking lipoxygenase gene in mice does not cause major defects in erythropoiesis.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] It is suggested that mitochondrial degradation proceeds through at least two redundant pathways besides that triggered by lipoxygenase-dependent formation of 13(*S*)-HpODE- and 13(*S*)-HODE-bound phospholipids viz., mitochondrial digestion by autophagy and mitochondrial exocytosis.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In all events, formation of 13(*S*)-HODE bound to phospholipid in mitochondrial membranes is one pathway by which they become more permeable and thereby subject to degradation and, as consequence of their release of deleterious elements, to cause cell injury.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These effects may contribute to the pro-inflammatory and tissue-injuring actions ascribed to 13-HODEs (and 9-HODEs).
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In atherosclerosis, an underlying cause of Coronary artery disease and strokes, atheromatous plaques accumulate in the vascular tunica intima thereby narrowing blood vessel size and decreasing blood flow.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In an animal model and in humans 13-HODE (primarily esterified to cholesterol, phospholipids, and possibly other lipids) is a dominant component of these plaques.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The 13(*S*)-HODE/PPARγ axis also causes macrophages to self-destruct by activating apoptosis-inducing pathways;, this effect may also contribute to increases in plaque size.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These studies suggest that 13-HODE-producing metabolic pathways, PPARγ, CD36, and aP2 may be therapeutic targets for treating atherosclerosis-related diseases.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Indeed, Statins, which are known to suppress cholesterol synthesis by inhibiting an enzyme in the cholesterol synthesis pathway, 3-hydroxy-3-methyl-glutaryl-CoA reductase HMG-CoA reductase, are widely used to prevent atherosclerosis and atherosclerosis-related diseases.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Statins also inhibit PPARγ in human macrophages, vascular endothelial cells, and smooth muscle cells; this action may contribute to their anti-atherogenic effect.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In guinea pigs, 13(*S*)-HODE, when injected intravenously, causes a narrowing of lung airways and, when inhaled as an aerosol, mimics the asthmatic hypersensitivity to agents that cause bronchoconstriction by increasing airway narrowing responses to methacholine and histamine.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Familial adenomatous polyposis is a syndrome that includes the propensity to develop colorectal cancer (and other cancers) due to the inheritance of defective mutations in either the APC (adenomatous polyposis coli) or MUTYH gene.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These mutations lead to several abnormalities in the regulation of the growth of colon epithelial cells that ultimately lead to the development of intestinal polyps which have a high risk of turning cancerous.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Similarly selective reductions in 15-lipoxygenase 1 and 13-HODE occur in non-hereditary colon cancer.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13(*S*)-HODE inhibits the proliferation and causes the death (apoptosis) of cultured human colon cancer cells.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Animal model studies also find that the 15-lipoxygenase 1 / 13-HODE axis inhibits the development of drug-induced colon cancer as well as the growth of human colon cancer cell explants.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The results of these studies suggest that 13(*S*)-HODE may act to promote the growth of breast cancer in humans.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These 15-LOX 1 effects appear due to the enzyme's production of 13(*S*)-HODE.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The 15-LOX 1/13(**S**)-HODE axis also promotes the growth of prostate cancer in various animal models.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In one animal model the pro-growth effects of 15-LOX 1 were altered by dietary targeting: increases in dietary linoleic acid, an omega-6 fatty acid, promoted while increases in dietary stearidonic acid, an omega-3 fatty acid reduced the growth of human prostate cancer explants.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The level of total HODEs, which includes various 13-HODE and 9-HODE isomers, are elevated in the plasma and erythrocytes of patients with Alzheimer's disease and in the plasma but not erythrocytes of patients with vascular dementia compared to normal volunteers.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] See 9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic acid section on 9-HODEs as markers of disease involving oxidative stress for further details.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These studies suggest that high levels of the HODEs may be useful to indicate the presence and progression of the cited diseases.
[src:basil/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] HODE markers may find usefulness as markers of specific disease, type of disease, and/or progression of disease when combined with other disease markers.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A subset of cytochrome P450 (CYP450) microsome-bound ω-hydroxylases, the cytochrome P450 omega hydroxylases, metabolize arachidonic acid to 20-HETE by an omega oxidation reaction.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] CYP450 enzymes belong to a superfamily which in humans is composed of at least 57 members and in mice at least 120 members.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] However, CYP2U1 may also contribute to the production of these two HETEs and CYP4F8 can metabolize arachidonic acid to 19-HETE while forming little or no 20-HETE.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The production of 19-HETE with 20-HETE may be significant since 19(*R*)-HETE, although not its stereoisomer, 19(*S*)-HETE, inhibits the action of 20-HETE on vascular endothelial cells.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Based on studies analyzing the production of other HETEs by CYP enzymes, the production of 19-HETE by these enzymes may include both its *R* and *S* stereoisomers.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In humans, the CYP4 ω-hydroxylases include CYP4A11, CYP4F2, and CYP4F3 with the predominant 20-HETE-synthesizing enzymes being CYP4F2, which is the major 20-HETE producing enzyme in the human kidney, followed by CYP4A11.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] CYP4F3 is expressed as two distinct enzymes, CYP4F3A and CYP4F3B, due to alternative splicing of a single pre-mRNA precursor molecule; CYP4F3A is mostly expressed in leukocytes, CYP4F3B mostly in the liver.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Human CYP4Z1, which is expressed in a limited range of tissues such as human breast and ovary, may also metabolize arachidonic acid to 20-HETE while human CYP4A22, once considered as contributing to 20-HETE production, is now regarded as being metabolically inactive.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Finally, CYP2U1, the only member of the human CYP2U subfamily, is highly expressed in brain and thymus and to lesser extents in numerous other tissues such as kidney, lung and heart.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] CYP2U1 protein is also highly expressed, compared to several other cytochrome P450 enzymes, in malignant breast tissue; the MCF-7 human breast cancer cell line express messenger RNA for this cytochrome.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In mice, the only 20-HETE- and 19-HETE-producing enzymes of the Cyp4a subfamily are two extensively homologous ones, Cyp4a12a and Cyp4a12b; Cyp4a12a is expressed in the male kidney in an androgen hormone-dependent manner.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The tissue distribution of these enzymes differs from those of humans making extrapolations from rodent studies to humans somewhat complicated.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Mouse CYP2J9, rat CYP2J3, and sheep CYP2J metabolize arachidonic acid primarily to 19-HETE but also to smaller amounts of 20-HETE, and, in the case of the sheep enzyme, 18-HETE; human CYP2J2, however, is an epoxygenase, metabolizing arachidonic acid to epoxide products.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Many agents stimulate cells and tissues to produce 20-HETE in vitro and in vivo.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Androgens are particularly potent stimulators of this production.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Other stimulators include the powerful vasoconstriction-inducing agents, angiotensin II, endothelins, and alpha adrenergic compounds (e.g. norepinephrine).
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Nitric oxide, carbon monoxide, and superoxide inhibit 20-HETE production; these non-pharmacological agents do so by binding to the Heme binding site of the 20-HETE producing cytochrome p450 enzymes.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Drugs that are substrates for the UDP-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT) enzymes which metabolize 20-HETE such as non-steroidal anti-inflammatory agents, opioids, gemfibrozil, Lasix, propanol, and various COX-2 inhibitors may act as perhaps unwanted side effects to increase the levels of 20-HETE.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] There are a variety of pharmacological agents which inhibit the synthesis of 20-HETE including various fatty acid analogs that compete reversibly with arachidonic acid for the substrate binding site in the CYP enzymes and benzene-based drugs.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The cytochrome ω-oxidases including those belonging to the CYP4A and CYP4F sub-families and CYPU21 hydroxylate not only arachidonic acid but also various shorter chain (e.g. lauric acid) and/or longer chain (e.g. docosahexaenoic acid) fatty acids.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] They can also ω-hydroxylate and thereby reduce the activity of various fatty acid metabolites (e.g.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] LTB4, 5-HETE, 5-oxo-eicosatetraenoic acid, 12-HETE, and several prostaglandins) that regulate inflammation, vascular responses, and other reactions.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] This metabolism-induced inactivation may underlie the proposed roles of the cytochromes in dampening inflammatory responses and the reported associations of certain CYP4F2 and CYP4F3 single nucleotide variants with human Krohn's disease and Coeliac disease, respectively.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Glucuronidation of 20-HETE by UDP-glucuronosyltransferases (UGTs) is thought to be a primary pathway of 20-HETE elimination and thereby inactivation in humans.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] There are several other pathways that metabolize 20-HETE.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] However, the 20-hydroxy prostaglandin metabolites are able to contract rat aorta rings and thereby could contribute to the hypertensive actions of 20-HETE.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Coronary artery endothelial cells isolated from pigs incorporate 20-HETE primarily into the sn-2 position of phospholipids through a coenzyme A-dependent process.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] It is likely, although not yet shown, that these mouse and pig 20-HETE metabolizing pathways also occur in humans.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE-synthesizing enzymes are widely distributed to liver, kidney, brain, lung, intestine and blood vessels.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In most vascular systems, 20-HETE synthesizing activity is limited to vascular smooth muscle of small blood vessels with little or no such activity in the vessel's endothelial cells or in large blood vessels.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] However, both the smooth muscle and endothelial cells obtained from mouse brain microvasculature, produce 20-HETE in culture.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE is produced by human neutrophils and platelets and by the ascending tubule cells in the medulla as well the pre-glomerular arterioles and certain other localized areas of the rabbit kidney.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Other agents such as Androgens and alpha adrenergic compounds such as norepinephrine. likewise stimulate 20-HETE production and have vasoconstrictive actions which are enhanced by 20-HETE.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These circular or positive feedback interactions may serve to perpetuate vasoconstrictor responses.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Again in rodent models, 20-HETE acts to block Calcium-activated potassium channels to promote the entry of ionic calcium into vascular smooth muscle cells through the L-type calcium channel; the attendant rise in intracellular calcium triggers these muscles to contract.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Studies in rats also indicate that in vascular endothelial cells 20-HETE inhibits the association of the nitric oxide-producing enzyme, endothelial nitric oxide synthase (eNOS) with heat shock protein 90; this inhibits the ability of eNOS to become activated.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE can also constrict rodent (and human) artery preparations by directly activating the receptor for thromboxane A2.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Acting in the latter capacity, 20-HETE, it is proposed, functions as a mediator regulating blood flow to the brain.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Sprague Dawley rats that underwent balloon injury of the common carotid artery exhibited elevated levels of CYP4A enzyme immunostaining in the smooth muscle of the injured arteries as well as elevated levels of 20-HETE in the injured arteries.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Inhibition of 20-HETE production by two different agents greatly reduced the vascular intima hyperplasia and vascular remodeling that occurred after balloon injury.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The studies suggest that the increase in expression of CYP4A and production of 20-HETE contribute to vascular intima growth, remolding, and thereby healing of injured rat carotid arteries.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The endothelial, platelet, and pro-clotting actions of 20-HETE may contribute to its ability to disrupt blood flood to tissues.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] As indicated above, 20-HETE may raise blood pressure by constricting arterial blood vessels but also may lower blood pressure by promoting the loss of sodium and fluids in the kidneys.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The effects of 20-HETE therefore are complex, as indicated in studies of the following animal models.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Spontaneously hypertensive rats exhibit elevated levels of CYP4A2 and 20-HETE; blockade of 20-HETE production lowers blood pressure in this model.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The effect is particularly well seen in female rats: aging post-menopausal but not pre-menopausal female spontaneously hypertensive rats exhibit highly significant falls in blood pressure when treated with non-selective or selective inhibitors of CYP-induced 20-HETE production.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Dahl salt-sensitive rats develop hypertension that develops more quickly and exacerbated by high intake of salt (sodium chloride) and ameliorated by low salt intake.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In this model, rats exhibit an up-regulated CYP4A/20-HETE pathway within their cerebral vasculature and vascular endothelial cell overproduction of reactive oxygen species that in turn stimulates the CYp4A/20-HETE pathway.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Non-selective and non-selective inhibitors of CYP4A and 20-HETE production reduce hypertension in this model.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The hypertension in this model is more severe in male rats and appears to be mediated at least in part by vasopressin, the renin-angiotensin system, and androgens.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Lewis rats (see Laboratory rat models) that had one kidney removed and then fed a high salt diet are hypertensive.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Androgen treatment causes hypertension in normal male and female rats; this hypertensive response is greatly reduced by diverse inhibitors of Cyp4a and 20-HETE production.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Cyp4a12-transgenic mice overexpressing Cyp4a12 develop androgen-independent hypertension that is associated with increased levels of 20-HETE; this hypertension is fully reversible by treatment with a Cyp4a selective inhibitor of 20-HETE production.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Mice depleted of Cyp4a14 by gene knockout (Cyp4a14(-/-) mice develop male-specific, androgen-dependent hypertension.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] This seemingly paradoxical result is due to the overexpression of Cyp4a12a; the knockout of Cyp4a14 (Cyp4a14 does not produce 20-HETE) leads to the overexpression of the 20-HETE-producing cytochrome, Cyp4a149(-/-), and consequent overproduction of 20-HETE.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The Cyp4a12-transgenic model (above) is referred to in support of this presumption.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Mice depleted of Cyp4a10 maintain normal blood pressure on a low salt diet but become hypertensive on normal or high salt diets; this paradoxical result appears due to a decrease in kidney levels of Cyp2C44 caused by the loss of Cyp4a10.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Cyp2C44 metabolizes arachidonic acid a family of vasodilation-inducing and anti-hypertensive products, the Epoxyeicosatrienoic acids (EETs).
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE activates the mouse and human transient receptor potential cation channel subfamily V member 1 (TRPV1, also known as the capsaicin receptor and the vanilloid receptor 1), and through this receptor, cultured dorsal root ganglion cells taken from mice.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Human CYP4A11 has 72.69% amino acid identity with murine cyp4a14 and 73.02% identity with murine cyp4a10 suggesting that it plays a role in humans similar to that of cyp4a14 and/or cyp4a10 in mice.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The association of hypertension with defective CYP4A11 in humans as indicated below seems to parallel the hypertension associated with Cyp4a14 gene knockout in mice (see above section on genetic models).
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The effect of the −296C>T single base pair substitution on baseline CYP411 transcriptional activity was not significant, suggesting that this polymorphism may not be the causal variant but instead may be in linkage disequilibrium with the causal variant.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Regardless, this SNP may serve as a genetic marker for large vessel disease stroke risk in this population.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] This variant of the CYP4F2 enzyme has reduced capacity to metabolize arachidonic acid to 20-HETE but increased urinary excretion of 20-HETE.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The maintenance of the lower blood pressure that followed diet-induced weight loss was more difficult for carriers of the Val433Met variant and may be related to increased arterial stiffness and increased 20-HETE synthesis.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The incidence of cerebral and myocardial infarction in these studies appears to be independent of hypertension.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] (The platelets of individuals heterozygous or homozygous for the Val433Met variant exhibit increased platelet aggregation responses to epinephrine.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The Single-nucleotide polymorphism rs1558139 guanine to cytosine variant in an intron of CYP4F2 is associated with essential hypertension in men only in a study of 249 hypertensive versus 238 age-matched controls in Japan.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The impact of this variant on CYP4F2 expression is not known.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Researchers have identified at least 3 more single-nucleotide polymorphisms of *CYP4F2* (2024C>G P85A; 80 C>T A27V rs771576634; 139C>T R47C rs115517770) which may affect conversion of arachidonic acid to HETE-20.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A mutation (c.947A>T) in CYP2U1 has been associated with a small number of patients with Hereditary spastic paraplegia in that it segregates with the disease at the homozygous state in two afflicted families.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A second homozygous enzyme-disabling mutation has been identified in CYP2U1, c.1A>C/p.Met1?, that is associated with <1% of hereditary spastic paraplegia sufferers.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] While the role of 20-HETE in these mutations has not been established, the reduction in 20-HETE production and thereby 20-HETE's activation of the TRPV1 receptor in nerve tissues, it is hypothesized, may contribute to the disease.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Two human breast cancer cell lines, T47D and BT-474, made to overexpress CYP4Z1 by transfection overexpress messenger RNA for and overproduce vascular endothelial growth factor A while under expressing message and protein for tissue inhibitor of metalloproteinase-2.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] T47D cells that overexpress CYP4Z1 also overproduce 20-HETE and when transplanted into athymic Balb/c mice show a greater increase in tumor weight and vascularity compared to control T47D cells; these increases are prevented by an inhibitor of 20-HETE production.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Isoliquiritigenin, a proposed drug for treating cancer, cause cultured MDA-MB-231 and MCF-7 human breast cancer cells to die by triggering apoptosis.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Among its many other effects, the drug caused these cells to decrease their levels of 20-HETE in vitro; the addition of 20-HETE to these cultures rescued the cells from apoptosis.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Isoliquiritigenin also inhibits the in vivo lung metastasis of MDA-MB-231 cell transplants while concurrently decreasing the tumor's levels of 20-HETE.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The growth of MDA-MB-231 cells implanted into athymic nude female mice as well as the cells' production of a large variety of agents stimulating vascularization including vascular endothelial growth factor were inhibited by treating the mice with an inhibitor of 20-HETE production.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Messenger RNAs not only for CYP4Z2 but also for CYP4A11, CYP4A22, CYP4F2, and CYP4F3 are more highly expressed in samples of human breast cancer tumors compared to normal breast tissue.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The Three prime untranslated regions (3'UTRs) of the CYP4Z1 gene and its Pseudogene, CYP4Z2P, share several miRNA-binding sites, including those for miR-211, miR-125a-3p, miR-197, miR-1226, and miR-204'.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Taken together, these pre-clinical studies suggest that 20-HETE made by one or more of the cited cytochrome P450 enzymes may contribute to the progression of breast cancer by promoting its survival, growth, and vascular endothelial growth factor-induced neovascularization.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE stimulated the proliferation of cultured human brain Glioma cell line U251 and, when forced to overexpress CYP4Z1 by gene transfection, overproduced 20-HETE and exhibited a dramatically increased rate of growth that was blocked by inhibiting the cells from producing 20-HETE.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A similar set of findings was found with human non-small cell lung cancer cells.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A selective inhibitor of 20-HETE synthesis and a 20-HETE antagonist reduced the growth of two human kidney cancer 786-O and 769-P cell lines in culture; the 20-HETE antagonist also inhibited the growth of 786-O cells transplanted into athymic nude mice.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Ovarian cancers also overexpress CYP4Z1 mRNA protein; this overexpression is associated with a poorer disease outcome.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] While these studies suggest that CYP4A11, CYP4A22, CYP4F2, and/or CYP4F3 produce 20-HETE which in turn promotes the growth of the cited cancers in model systems and therefore may do so in the human cancers, this suggestion clearly needs much further study.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] It is also possible that any such inhibitor has off-target effects that are responsible for its actions.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE inhibits the aggregation of human platelets by competing with arachidonic acid for the enzymes that produce prostaglandin H2 and thromboxane A2.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These products are formed in response to platelet stimulation and then act through the thromboxane receptor to mediate and/or promote the ensuing platelet aggregation response to most stimuli.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The platelets metabolize 20-HETE to the 20-hydroxy analogs of prostaglandin H2 and thromboxane A2, products that are essentially inactive in platelets, while consequently form less of the arachidonic acid-derived prostaglandin and thromboxane products.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In addition, 20-HETE itself blocks prostaglandin and thromboxane metabolites from interacting with the thromboxane receptor.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Both effects, i.e. replacement of prostaglandin and thromboxane production with platelet-inactive products and thromboxane A2 receptor blockade, are responsible for 20-HETE's platelet aggregation-inhibiting action.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] However, the platelet anti-aggregating activity of 20-HETE requires micromolar levels and therefore may be more of a pharmacological than physiological activity.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE constricts human artery preparations by directly activating the receptor for thromboxane A2.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Acting in the latter capacity, 20-HETE, it is proposed, functions as a mediator regulating blood flow to the human brain.
[src:basil/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] One study found that 30 patients with the metabolic syndrome exhibited significantly elevated levels of plasma and urinary 20-HETE compared to matched controls; women with the syndrome had particularly higher urinary 20-HETE levels.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] Early identification and characterization of 4-hydroxynonenal was reported by Esterbauer, et al., who also obtained the same compound synthetically.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] The topic has since been often reviewed, and one source describes the compound as "the most studied LPO (lipid peroxidation) product with pleiotropic capabilities".
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] 4-Hydroxynonenal is generated in the oxidation of lipids containing polyunsaturated omega-6 fatty acids, such as arachidonic and linoleic acids, and of their 15-lipoxygenase metabolites, namely 15-hydroperoxyeicosatetraenoic and 13-hydroperoxyoctadecadienoic acids.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] Although they are the most studied ones, in the same process other oxygenated α,β-unsaturated aldehydes (OαβUAs) are generated also, which can also come from omega-3 fatty acids, such as 4-oxo-trans-2-nonenal, 4-hydroxy-trans-2-hexenal, 4-hydroperoxy-trans-2-nonenal and 4,5-epoxy-*trans*-2-decenal.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] 4-HNE can attach to proteins via a Michael addition reaction, which can target cysteine, histidine or lysine, or through the formation of a Schiff base, which can target arginine or lysine.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] The lysine adduct ((4-HNE)-lysine or 4-hydroxynonenallysine) has been referred to as an "oxidation-specific epitope" and a lipid oxidation "degradation product".
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] It is generated by the oxidative modification of low-density lipoprotein through the direct addition of carbonyl groups from 4-HNE onto lysine.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] These compounds can be produced in cells and tissues of living organisms or in foods during processing or storage, and from these latter can be absorbed through the diet.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] Since 1991, OαβUAs are receiving a great deal of attention because they are being considered as possible causal agents of numerous diseases, such as chronic inflammation, neurodegenerative diseases, adult respiratory distress syndrome, atherogenesis, diabetes and different types of cancer.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] HNE has been linked to the pathology of several diseases such as Alzheimer's disease, cataract, atherosclerosis, diabetes and cancer.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] The increasing trend to enrich foods with polyunsaturated acyl groups entails the potential risk of enriching the food with some OαβUAs at the same time, as has already been detected in some studies carried out in 2007.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] PUFA-fortified foods available on the market have been increasing since epidemiological and clinical researches have revealed possible effects of PUFA on brain development and curative and/or preventive effects on cardiovascular disease.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] However, PUFA are very labile and easily oxidizable, thus the maximum beneficial effects of PUFA supplements may not be obtained if they contain significant amounts of toxic OαβUAs, which as commented on above, are being considered as possible causal agents of numerous diseases.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] Special attention must also be paid to cooking oils used repeatedly in catering and households because in those processes very high amounts of OαβUAs are generated and they can be easily absorbed through the diet.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] 4-HNE has two reactive groups: the conjugated aldehyde and the C=C double-bond, and the hydroxy group at carbon 4.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] The α,β-unsaturated ketone serves as a Michael acceptor, adding thiols to give thioether adducts.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] A small group of enzymes are specifically suited to the detoxification and removal of 4-HNE from cells.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] Within this group are the glutathione S-transferases (GSTs) such as hGSTA4-4 and hGST5.8, aldose reductase, and aldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] These enzymes have low Km values for HNE catalysis and together are very efficient at controlling the intracellular concentration, up to a critical threshold amount, at which these enzymes are overwhelmed and cell death is inevitable.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] Glutathione S-transferases hGSTA4-4 and hGST5.8 catalyze the conjugation of glutathione peptides to 4-hydroxynonenal through a conjugate addition to the alpha-beta unsaturated carbonyl, forming a more water-soluble molecule, GS-HNE.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] This result strongly suggests that hGSTA4-4 and hGST5.8 are specifically adapted by human cells for the purpose of detoxifying 4-HNE to abrogate the downstream effects which such a buildup would cause.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] Increased activity of the mitochondrial enzyme aldehyde dehydrogenase 2 (ALDH2) has been shown to have a protective effect against cardiac ischemia in animal models, and the postulated mechanism given by the investigators was 4-hydroxynonenal metabolism.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] GS-HNE is a potent inhibitor of the activity of glutathione S-transferase, and therefore must be shuttled out of the cell to allow conjugation to occur at a physiological rate.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] Ral-interacting GTPase activating protein (RLIP76, also known as Ral-binding protein 1), is a membrane-bound protein which has high activity towards the transport of GS-HNE from the cytoplasm to the extracellular space.
[src:basil/4-hydroxynonenal] This protein accounts for approximately 70% of such transport in human cell lines, while the remainder appears to be accounted for by Multidrug Resistance Protein 1 (MRP1).
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Some recent studies measuring HODE levels in tissue have lumped the four 9-HODEs and four 13-HODEs together to report only on total HODEs (tHODEs): tHODEs have been proposed to be markers for certain human disease.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The enzymes cyclooxygenase 1 (COX-1) and cyclooxygenase 2 (COX-2), which are best known for metabolizing arachidonic acid to prostaglandins, are also able to metabolize linoleic acid predominantly to 9(*R*)-hydroperoxy-10(*E*),12(*Z*)-octadecadienoic acid (i.e.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 9(*S*)-HpODE); in cells and tissues, the two hydroperoxy metabolites are rapidly reduce to 9(*R*)-HODE and 9(*S*)-HODE, respectively.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] COX-2 exhibits a greater preference for linoleic acid than does Cox-1 and is therefore credited with producing most of these products in cells expressing both COX enzymes.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In cells and tissues, the cytochrome enzymes concurrently metabolize linoleic acid to 13(*S*)-HpODE and 13(*R*)-HpODE which are reduced to 13(*S*)-HODE and 13(*R*)-HODE in an *R*/*S* ratio similar to than of the 9-HODES, i.e.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Free-radical oxidation of linoleic acid produces racemic mixtures of 9-HODE and 9-EE-HODE; singlet-oxygen attack on linoleic acid produces (presumably) racemic mixtures of 9-HODE, 10-hydroxy-8*E*,12*Z*-octadecadienoic acid, and 12-hydroxy-9*Z*-13-*E*-octadecadienoic acid.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The murine homolog of human 15(*S*)-lipoxygenase-2 (ALOX15B), 8(*S*)-lipoxygenase, while preferring arachidonic acid over linoleic acid, metabolizes linoleic acid predominantly to (9(*S*)-HpODE, which in tissues and cells is rapidly reduced to 9(*S*)-HODE.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] However, ALOX15B, similar to human 15-lipoxygenase-1 (ALOX15), metabolizes linoleic acid to 13(*S*)-HODE but not to 9(*S*)-HODEs.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 9-HODE esterified to the sn-2 position of phosphatidylserine is subject to be released as free 9-HODE by the action of cytosol (see phospholipase A2 section on cPLA2) and therefore may serve as a storage pool that is mobilized by cell stimulation.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 9-HODE may be further metabolized to 9-oxo-10(*E*),12(*Z*)-octadecadienoic acid (9-oxoODE or 9-oxo-ODE), possibly by the same hydroxy-fatty-acid dehydrogenase which metabolizes other hydroxy fatty acids, such as 13-HODE, to their oxo derivatives.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 9-HODE, 9-oxoODE, and 9-EE-HODE (along with their 13-HODE counterparts) directly activate peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPARγ).
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 9(*S*)-HODE and with progressively lesser potencies 9(*S*)-HpODE, a racemic mixture of 9-HODE, 13(*S*)-HpODE, and 13(*S*)-HODE directly activate human (but not mouse) GPR132 (i.e.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] G protein coupled receptor 132 or G2A) in Chinese hamster ovary cells made to express these receptors; 9(*S*)-HODE was also a more potent stimulator of human G2A than a series of mono-hydroxy arachidonic acid metabolites.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] HODEs measurements have been evaluated as markers for many of these oxygen-stress-related diseases.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These measurements commonly use saponification methods to release HODEs bound by acylation to other molecules; they therefore measure not only free HODEs but also HODEs acylated to phospholipids, glycerides, cholesterol, and other lipids.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Some of the studies cited above have suggested that 9-HODEs, 13-HODEs, their hydroperoxy counterparts, and/or their oxo counterparts contribute mechanistically to these oxidative-stress-related diseases.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] That is, the free radical oxidation of linoleic acid makes these products which then proceed to contribute to the tissue injury, DNA damage, and/or systemic dysfunctions that characterize the diseases.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Furthermore, certain of these HODE-related products may serve as signals to activate pathways that combat the reactive oxygen species and in this and other ways the oxidative stress.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] It remains unclear whether or not the HODEs and their counterparts promote, dampen, or merely reflect oxidative-stress-related diseases.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 9(*S*)-HODE, 9(*R*)-HODE, and 9-oxoODE, along with the other OXLAMs, appear to act through the TRPV1 receptor (see above section on Direct actions) mediate the perception of acute and chronic pain induced by heat, UV light, and inflammation in the skin of rodents.
[src:basil/9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These studies propose that the OXLAM-TRPV1 circuit (with 9(*S*)-HODE being the most potent TRPV1-activating OXLAM) similarly contributes to the perception of pain in humans.
[src:basil/basil] There are many varieties of basil including sweet basil, Thai basil (*O. basilicum* var.
[src:basil/basil] *O. basilicum* can cross-pollinate with other species of the *Ocimum* genus, producing hybrids such as lemon basil (*O.* × *africanum*) and African blue basil (*O.* × *kilimandscharicum*).
[src:basil/basil] Basil is an annual, or sometimes perennial, herb.
[src:basil/basil] Depending on the variety, plants can reach heights of between 30 and 150 centimetres (1 and 5 feet).
[src:basil/basil] Basil leaves are glossy and ovate, with smooth or slightly toothed edges that typically cup slightly; the leaves are arranged oppositely along the square stems.
[src:basil/basil] Its flowers are small and white, and grow from a central inflorescence, or spike, that emerges from the central stem atop the plant.
[src:basil/basil] Unusual among Lamiaceae, the four stamens and the pistil are not pushed under the upper lip of the corolla, but lie over the inferior lip.
[src:basil/basil] After entomophilous pollination, the corolla falls off and four round achenes develop inside the bilabiate calyx.
[src:basil/basil] The various basils have such distinct scents because the volatile aromatic compounds vary with cultivars.
[src:basil/basil] The essential oil from European basil contains high concentrations of linalool and methyl chavicol (estragole), in a ratio of about 3:1.
[src:basil/basil] Other constituents include: 1,8-cineole, eugenol, and myrcene, among others.
[src:basil/basil] The clove scent of sweet basil is derived from eugenol.
[src:basil/basil] The aroma profile of basil includes 1,8-cineole and methyl eugenol.
[src:basil/basil] In this species eugenol is synthesised from coniferyl acetate and NADPH.
[src:basil/basil] Some similar species in the same genus may be commonly called "basil", although they are not varieties of *Ocimum basilicum*.
[src:basil/basil] The exact taxonomy of basil is uncertain due to the immense number of cultivars, its ready polymorphy, and frequent cross-pollination (resulting in new hybrids) with other members of the genus *Ocimum* and within the species.
[src:basil/basil] *Ocimum basilicum* has at least 60 varieties, which further complicates taxonomy.
[src:basil/basil] Most basils are cultivars of sweet basil.
[src:basil/basil] Most basil varieties have green leaves, but a few are purple, such as, 'Purple Delight'.
[src:basil/basil] The name "basil" comes from the Latin *basilius*, and the Greek βασιλικόν φυτόν (*basilikón phytón*), meaning "royal/kingly plant", possibly because the plant was believed to have been used in production of royal perfumes.
[src:basil/basil] Basil is likewise sometimes referred to in French as *"l'herbe royale"* ('the royal herb').
[src:basil/basil] The Latin name has been confused with basilisk, as it was supposed to be an antidote to the basilisk's venom.
[src:basil/basil] Basil is native to India and other tropical regions stretching from Africa to South East Asia, but has now become globalized due to human cultivation.
[src:basil/basil] Basil is sensitive to cold, with best growth in hot, dry conditions.
[src:basil/basil] Basil prefers high light conditions and grows best under full sun conditions.
[src:basil/basil] Increasing light intensity, particularly the photosynthetic photon flux density, can significantly enhance the plant's fresh weight, dry matter content, and height.
[src:basil/basil] However, due to its common use, basil is cultivated in many countries around the world.
[src:basil/basil] Production areas include countries in the Mediterranean area, those in the temperate zone, and others in subtropical climates.
[src:basil/basil] Additionally, it may be sown in soil once chance of frost is past.
[src:basil/basil] It fares best in well-drained soil with direct exposure to the sun.
[src:basil/basil] Although basil grows best outdoors, it can be grown indoors in a pot and, like most herbs, will do best on a sun-facing windowsill, kept away from cold drafts.
[src:basil/basil] A greenhouse or row cover is ideal if available.
[src:basil/basil] It can, however, even be grown in a basement under fluorescent lights.
[src:basil/basil] Supplemental lighting produces greater biomass and phenol production, with red + blue specifically increasing growth and flower bud production.
[src:basil/basil] UV-B increases the volatiles in *O. basilicum* essential oil, which has not been reproducible in other plants, and so may be unique to the genus or even to this species.
[src:basil/basil] Basil prefers well-drained organic soils, as adequate oxygen availability in the root zone is essential for optimal plant growth.
[src:basil/basil] Poor soil drainage can lead to root hypoxia, which negatively affects overall plant development and essential oil yield.
[src:basil/basil] Once a stem produces flowers, foliage production stops on that stem, the stem becomes woody, and essential oil production declines.
[src:basil/basil] To prevent this, a basil-grower may pinch off any flower stems before they are fully mature.
[src:basil/basil] Because only the blooming stem is so affected, some stems can be pinched for leaf production, while others are left to bloom for decoration or seeds.
[src:basil/basil] Picking the leaves off the plant helps promote growth, largely because the plant responds by converting pairs of leaflets next to the topmost leaves into new stems.
[src:basil/basil] Once the plant is allowed to flower, it may produce seed pods containing small black seeds, which can be saved and planted the following year.
[src:basil/basil] If allowed to go to seed, a basil plant will grow back the next year.
[src:basil/basil] The optimal germination temperature for basil seeds ranges between 34.5–39.0°C, while the base germination temperature lies between 9.8–13.2°C.
[src:basil/basil] No significant variation in optimal germination temperature has been observed among different basil cultivars.
[src:basil/basil] Prior to sowing, basil (*Ocimum basilicum*) seeds can be hydroprimed by soaking in water for 12 hours, which effectively enhances germination rates and seedling vigor.
[src:basil/basil] Basil (*Ocimum basilicum* L.) is commonly propagated through cuttings.
[src:basil/basil] Compared to seed propagation, basil cuttings tend to result in earlier harvest and higher yield.
[src:basil/basil] The typical propagation method involves selecting healthy, non-lignified stem segments approximately 5–10 cm in length, preferably apical shoots that retain 2 to 5 leaves, which are then inserted into moist soil until root development occurs.
[src:basil/basil] After rooting, the plantlets are transplanted into the field.
[src:basil/basil] Exposing basil cuttings to blue light significantly accelerates root formation, thereby shortening the growth period.
[src:basil/basil] Basil suffers from several plant pathogens that can ruin the crop and reduce yield.
[src:basil/basil] Fusarium wilt is a soil-borne fungal disease that will quickly kill younger basil plants.
[src:basil/basil] Seedlings may be killed by *Pythium* damping off.
[src:basil/basil] A common foliar disease of basil is gray mold caused by *Botrytis cinerea*; it can cause infections post-harvest and is capable of killing the entire plant.
[src:basil/basil] Black spot can be seen on basil foliage and is caused by the fungi genus *Colletotrichum*.
[src:basil/basil] Downy mildew caused by *Peronospora belbahrii* is a significant disease, as first reported in Italy in 2003.
[src:basil/basil] It was reported in the Florida in 2007 and by 2008 had spread along the eastern United States, reaching Canada.
[src:basil/basil] Basil cultivars resistant to *P. belbahrii* have been developed.
[src:basil/basil] Non-pathogenic bacteria found on basil include *Novosphingobium* species.
[src:basil/basil] Basil is most commonly used fresh in recipes.
[src:basil/basil] In general, it is added last, as cooking quickly destroys the flavor.
[src:basil/basil] The fresh herb can be kept for a short time in plastic bags in the refrigerator, or for a longer period in the freezer, after being blanched quickly in boiling water.
[src:basil/basil] It has a flavor resembling that of liquorice.
[src:basil/basil] The most commonly used Mediterranean basil cultivars are "Genovese", "Purple Ruffles", "Mammoth", "Cinnamon", "Lemon", "Globe", and "African Blue".
[src:basil/basil] Basil is one of the main ingredients in pesto, an Italian sauce with olive oil and basil as its primary ingredients, and is used in other sauces and salad dressings.
[src:basil/basil] Many national cuisines use fresh or dried basils in soups and other foods, such as to thicken soups.
[src:basil/basil] Basil is commonly steeped in cream or milk to create flavor in ice cream or chocolate truffles.
[src:basil/basil] It is sometimes used to infuse oils and vinegars.
[src:basil/basil] Lemon basil has a strong lemony smell and flavor due to the presence of citral.
[src:basil/basil] It is widely used in Indonesia, where it is called *kemangi* and served raw as an accompaniment to meat or fish.
[src:basil/basil] When soaked in water, the seeds of several basil varieties become gelatinous, and are used in Asian drinks and desserts such as the Indian *faluda*, the Iranian *sharbat-e-rihan*, or *hột é*.
[src:basil/basil] In Kashmir, the Ramadan fast is often broken with *babre beole*, a sharbat made with basil seeds.
[src:basil/basil] Basil is used in folk medicine practices, such as those of Ayurveda or traditional Chinese medicine.
[src:basil/basil] Studies of the essential oil have shown insecticidal and insect-repelling properties, including potential toxicity to mosquitos.
[src:basil/basil] The essential oil is found by Huignard et al.
[src:basil/basil] 2008 to inhibit electrical activity by decreasing action potential amplitude, by shortening the post hyperpolarization phase, and reducing the action frequency of action potentials.
[src:basil/basil] In Huignard's opinion this is due to the linalool and estragole, the amplitude reduction due to linalool, and the phase shortening due to both.
[src:basil/basil] The essential oil is found by Malik et al.
[src:basil/basil] 1990 to be nematicidal against *Tylenchulus semipenetrans*, *Meloidogyne javanica*, *Anguina tritici*, and *Heterodera cajani*.
[src:basil/basil] The essential oil of the leaf and terminal shoot is effective against a large number of bacterial species including *Lactiplantibacillus plantarum* and *Pseudomonas* spp.
[src:basil/basil] The essential oil of the leaf and terminal shoot is also effective against a large number of fungal species including *Aspergillus* spp., *Candida* spp., *Mucor* spp., and *Geotrichum candidum*.
[src:basil/basil] There are many rituals and beliefs associated with basil.
[src:basil/basil] The ancient Egyptians and ancient Greeks believed basil would open the gates of heaven for a person passing on.
[src:basil/basil] However, Herbalist Nicholas Culpeper saw basil as a plant of dread and suspicion, citing warnings against consumption by authors such as Galen and Chrysippus.
[src:basil/basil] In Portugal, dwarf bush basil is traditionally presented in a pot, together with a poem and a paper carnation, to a sweetheart, on the religious holidays of John the Baptist (see Saint John's Eve § Portugal) and Saint Anthony of Padua.
[src:basil/basil] Basil has religious significance in the Greek Orthodox Church, where it is used to sprinkle holy water.
[src:basil/basil] The Bulgarian Orthodox Church, Serbian Orthodox Church, Macedonian Orthodox Church and Romanian Orthodox Church use basil (Bulgarian: босилек, *bosilek*; Serbian: босиљак, *bosiljak*; Macedonian: босилек, *bosilek*) to prepare holy water and pots of basil are often placed below church altars.
[src:basil/basil] Some Greek Orthodox Christians avoid eating it due to its association with the legend of the Elevation of the Holy Cross.
[src:basil/basil] In Giovanni Boccaccio's 14th century *Decameron*, the fifth story of the narrative's fourth day involves a pot of basil as a central plot device.
[src:basil/basil] This famous story inspired John Keats to write his 1814 poem "Isabella, or the Pot of Basil", which was in turn the inspiration for two paintings of the Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood: John Everett Millais's *Isabella* in 1849 and in 1868 the *Isabella and the Pot of Basil* by William Holman Hunt.
